The paper deals with adaptive group testing, which involves designing algorithms to identify defective items in a pool of items by testing subsets of them. This is a problem that has applications in various fields, including computer science, biology, and statistics. The paper focuses on the linear regime, where the number of defective items scales linearly with the number of items. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the fundamental limits of communication and information processing. Additionally, the paper involves designing algorithms, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial and probabilistic analysis, which suggests that it could belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper involves statistical analysis, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
